Change has been successfully merged

It looks like the variable might be uninitialized.

Before entering the loop please initialize it to 0: `_failSafePercent = 0;`

we can't initialize original zone _failSafePercent from the config file , our concept is
to take the max of (zone failsafepercent and pidloops failsafe percent) to be a final _failSafePercent for this zone

Understood. How about this, instead: I suggest adding another variable `_zoneFailSafePercent` and initializing it in the constructor, to receive the zone-wide failsafe value that the user has configured. That will preserve it, for later use.

Following your suggestion, I have added _zoneFailSafePercent and assigned the Fail Safe Percent value to the Zone during initialization.
With this change, the below comments have also been updated. Thank you.

Please use modern C++ "for each" syntax: `for (auto it : _pidsFailSafePercent)`

Also, unless needing to make a copy of the variable, use `const auto&` instead of `auto`
It looks like this comment has been taken care of. Please mark "Resolved" for comments that have been solved.
In this example, where does 70 come from?
I made a mistake accidentally, thank you for pointing it out.
it seems typing error , will fix it
Mark resolced

I like the idea of preserving the zone-wide user-configured failsafe value as a separate variable. Then, projects that use https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-pid-control/+/38112 can adapt as necessary, and it will be easier to avoid breaking them.
This is done, thanks, marking resolved.

If the zone-wide failsafe percent is preserved (see other comment), then `_failSafePercent` can be initialized here: `_failSafePercent = _zoneFailSafePercent;`

That would make this function idempotent.
Mark Resolved

It might be a good idea to maintain the zone-wide failsafe configuration value separately. That would make the `initPidFailSafePercent` function idempotent. For example `_zoneFailSafePercent(failSafePercent)`
Mark Resolved
The test cases were ran, and they passed, right?
Yes, we have tested it, and all the functionalities are working properly.

This should be initialized to NaN, not zero. We need to be properly warned about uninitialized data. By adding a literal initializer here, the compiler warning is defeated, so we will no longer be able to know about warnings at compile time.

If ReadReturn is ever used before it is populated, then we still need to know about this error condition. Initializing it here with a value of NaN will allow us to see this error at runtime, which is a fair compromise.

I got it, thank you.
Based on your suggestion, I have changed it to initialize as NAN, and the same modification has been modified in another commit (disable pid loop).
